article.description: UConn put the nation back on alert that the Huskies are still dangerous.
article.headline: Well-rested Taurasi, UConn back to true form

images.name: Taurasi Diana 030323 vert inline
images.caption: After some time to rest, Diana Taurasi looked like herself again on Sunday.

article.linkText: Seems like old times for UConn
article.story:
STORRS, Conn. (AP) -- Diana Taurasi had her game back and
top-seeded Connecticut had the look of a winner again Sunday as the
Huskies rebounded in a big way from their first loss in two years.

	   "We were ready to play. Everybody had the glance in their eye
that we had to start playing well and it had to start today,'' said
Taurasi, who scored 21 points in UConn's 91-44 win over Boston
University in the opening round of the East Regional.

<photo1>

	   The junior All-American also finished with seven assists,
shaking off the chronic ankle and back pain that has hampered her
the last few weeks.

	   It's been nearly two weeks since Villanova snapped UConn's
70-game win streak with a 52-48 upset in the Big East tournament
finals, enough time to heal mentally and physically.

	   "I think everyone hit a wall,'' Taurasi said. "A week and a
half really helped us to regroup.''

	   Taurasi's crisp passing and outside shooting -- she went 4-of-7
on 3-pointers -- helped carry the defending national champions into
a second-round game against ninth-seeded Texas Christian.

	   Adrienne Norris led the Terriers (16-15) with 16 points. Katie
Terhune finished with 11 before fouling out in the closing minutes.

	   "When (Taurasi) is playing well then we all look good, and she
played exceptionally well today,'' Huskies coach Geno Auriemma
said.

	   Despite the loss to Villanova, UConn entered the NCAA Tournament
as a No. 1 seed for the ninth time.

	   UConn spoiled the Terriers' tournament debut with smothering
defense and an up-tempo offense, posting its third-highest point
total of the season on 57 percent shooting.

	   UConn took the opening tip, raced down the court and scored in
the first four seconds on Ann Strother's inside basket. Two more
quick inside baskets from Barbara Turner and the Huskies were on
their way to a 19-5 opening run.

	   The 16th-seeded Terriers, champions of the America East
tournament, never recovered and were down by 27 points at halftime.

	   "We came in trying to play the best 40 minutes of basketball
that we've played all year,'' BU coach Margaret McKeon said.
"Obviously, UConn can take you out of a lot of things. Their
pressure early put us back on our heels.''

	   There was little let up in the second half as Taurasi nailed
consecutive 3s in the first three minutes and UConn opened with a
17-5 run. She played just eight minutes in the second half, but by
then the game was decided. Taurasi also finished with a blocked
shot and two of UConn's 10 steals.

	   Turner had 15 points, and Strother 16. Turner also anchored a
dominating inside game, grabbing 10 rebounds as UConn finished with
a 46-21 edge on the boards.

	   "They way we practiced last week carried over into the game,''
Strother said. "Hopefully, we'll keep carrying it.''

	   The Huskies outscored BU 48-14 in the paint and got 30 points
off 18 turnovers. UConn shot 11-of-25 (44 percent) from behind the
arc.

	   "When you make shots everything looks good,'' Auriemma said.
"In the Villanova game we didn't make any shots so we looked
horrible and we stood around and we pouted. Today we got the game
going the way we wanted it to go.''
